data.content:
In xUnit, the setup/teardown pattern is fundamentally different:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture |

Here's your converted class:

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **Per-test setup/teardown**: xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor and `Dispose()` naturally replace `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`.
- **One-time setup/teardown**: Extract into a fixture class implementing `IDisposable`, then declare `IClassFixture<T>` on your test class. The fixture is injected via the constructor and shared across all tests in the class.
- **Assertions**: `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` → `Assert.NotNull(x)`; `Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))` → `Assert.Equal(y, x)` (note: expected comes first).
